- if you make a function that takes an object as a parameter and the function changes a property, the property is permannetly changed.


- if you make a function that takes an object as a parameter and the function changes the object, the object won't change even if its declared with let keyword.




#### Basic Object
```js
// Raw Object
const bird = {
  name: "Albert",
  color: "blue",
  numLegs: 2,
};
```
#### Access Object Properties

:::note
We must use bracket notation when accessing keys that have numbers, spaces, or special characters in them. Without bracket notation in these situations, our code would throw an error.
:::
![](image-l4m4w1xv.png)


```js
// Using dot notation
bird.name

// Using square notation (Good for Variables)
bird["name"]
```


#### Method Declaration

```js  
const bird = {
    // Properties
    name: 'bob',
    age: 3,
    email: 'bob@gmail.com',
    aliases: ['pest', 'rat', 'pigeon'],


    // Method Declaration 1
    poop1: function () {
        console.log("poop1");
    },
    // Method Declaration 2 - Shorthand Method
    poop2() {
        console.log(this.aliases);
    },
    // Method Declaration 3 - Arrow Function
    poop3: () => {
        console.log(this.name);
    },
    // Method Declaration 4 - Regular FUnction
    poop4: function () {
        console.log(this.name);
    }
}


````
#### this Keyword


:::note
* Inside an object method with arrow functions there are no binding of this.
* if the method uses a conventional function this keyword will be used within the object scope
:::

```js  
const bird = {
     // Method Declaration 3 arrow function
    poop3: () => {
        console.log(this.name);
    },
    // Method Declaration 4 regular function 
    poop4: function () {
        console.log(this.name);
    }
 }   

// Will refer to the window object
bird.poop3()

// Will refer to the bird object
bird.poop4()
```



















## Basic Object Syntax
```js

// Object Constructor Function
function Bird(name, color) {
  this.color = color;
  this.numLegs = 2;
  this.name = name;
}



// Creating Object from Constructor

let pidgeon = new Bird("Michael", "Blue");

// Access Properties
console.log(pidgeon.name);
console.log(pidgeon.color);

// Override Property
pidgeon.name = "Carlos";
console.log(pidgeon.name);

// Create new Property
pidgeon.age = 12;
console.log(pidgeon.age);
```






## Creating Object Constructor with Methods
```js

var Person = function (firstAndLast) {
  // Hidden Variable
  let fullName = firstAndLast.split(" ");

  // Set Full Name
  this.setFullName = function (firstAndLast) {
    fullName[0] = firstAndLast.split(" ")[0];
    fullName[1] = firstAndLast.split(" ")[1];
  };
  // Set First Name
  this.setFirstName = function (firstName) {
    fullName[0] = firstName;
  };
  // Set Last Name
  this.setLastName = function (lastName) {
    fullName[1] = lastName;
  };

  // Get Full Name
  this.getFullName = function () {
    return fullName[0] + " " + fullName[1];
  };
  // Get First Name
  this.getFirstName = function () {
    return fullName[0];
  };
  // Get Last Name
  this.getLastName = function () {
    return fullName[1];
  };
};
```
